<P>
Photo, A Commingling of Species: The Bolsa Chica Ecological Reserve lets people 
observe a variety of birds in a natural setting. Its 1,635 acres constitute 
California's largest remaining coastal salt marsh, home to the least tern and 
Belding's Savannah sparrow, and a way station for migrating ducks, herons, 
geese and hundreds of other birds. At right, a tern skimming through the sky 
with a bit of fish in its beak is a sight for Barbara Turner, left above, of 
Long Beach and her mother, Florence Turner. Below, three black-necked stilt 
stand along the shore as three others lift off the water; Dick Purvis watches 
from a hiding place among the weeds. PETER ROSS / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
