<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Equal Justice for 'Equalizer' Suit: Hollywood writer and producer Lou Shaw has 
a legitimate right to pursue a copyright infringement suit over the pilot 
script for the "Equalizer" television series, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of 
Appeals in San Francisco ruled Tuesday. The appeals court said there was 
"substantial similarity" between a copyright script called "The Equalizer," 
written by Shaw in 1979, and the series pilot that appeared in 1985, allowing 
Shaw to sue the show's creators. The decision sent the case back to U.S. 
District Court in Pasadena, which had previously dismissed Shaw's claims. BETH 
KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071990-0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 249182 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 19, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
265 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: VIDEO RENTALS; 
</P>
<P>
'STEEL' GETS A GRIP ON FIRST PLACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS HUNT , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Steel Magnolias," the all-star female drama that's a big hit among female 
renters, swept past second-ranked "Tango and Cash" to the top of the Billboard 
magazine rental chart. The strongest new competitor for the No. 1 position is 
"The War of the Roses." 
</P>
<P>
Fans are so fascinated by the warring Roses that this black comedy rocketed to 
No. 4 in just two weeks. Look for it to take over the top spot sometime in the 
next few weeks. "We're No Angels," with Robert DeNiro and Sean Penn -- a 
lukewarm attraction when it played theaters -- is doing just modest rental 
business, moving up four notches to No. 19. "Family Business," the star-studded 
(Sean Connery and Dustin Hoffman) box-office dud, debuted at No. 31. 
</P>
<P>
* Expected to be one of the mightiest box-office hits last Christmas, 
"She-Devil" turned out to be one of the season's biggest bombs -- pulling in a 
meager $14.5 million. Fans didn't turn out in bunches to see TV star Roseanne 
Barr sparring with Meryl Streep for the affections of Ed Begley Jr. This comedy 
hasn't been a rental smash either, but its star power has attracted some 
renters. No. 12 after two weeks, it could crack the Top 10 next week. 
</P>
