<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: MOVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
All the World's a Stooge: Wanna chat with Larry, Moe and Curly? Just call the 
Three Stooges Hotline at (900) 860-9900 and you can hear those pie-throwing 
knuckleheads. The phone line, which opened last week and runs until September, 
was created for Columbia Pictures Merchandising by Phone Programs Inc. BETH 
KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071990-0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 249184 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 19, 1990, Thursday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
147 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NIBBLES AND BITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Kenneth Williams 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Laguna Art Museum has been awarded -- and has accepted -- two grants 
totaling $9,000 for collection, maintenance and conservation from the National 
Endowment for the Arts. The grants are being accepted, despite what amounts to 
a mandatory oath not to promote obscene artworks with the federal funds, said 
museum director Charles Desmarais. 
</P>
<P>
A letter of protest will be sent with the grant acceptance forms, however. The 
letter will not state non-compliance with the oath, but will note the museum's 
objection to it, Desmarais said. The NEA has said that grantees are not free to 
select from among 29 conditions of funding which they will or will not obey. 
The two NEA grants bring to three the museum has accepted this year. About 10 
NEA grant recipients around the country, none of them in Orange County, have 
rejected their awards to protest the obscenity clause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
