<HEADLINE>
<P>
MICROWAVE: JUICY SPARERIBS SHORTCUT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEAN ANDERSON and ELAINE HANNA, Anderson and Hanna are nutritionists and 
cookbook authors specializing in microwave cookery. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Barbecue spareribs in a microwave? You bet -- and in half the usual time. In 
fact, ribs that have been microwaved are supremely juicy and tender because of 
the microwave's moist method of cooking. 
</P>
<P>
If you like ribs crusty brown, simply finish them off in the broiler or on an 
outdoor grill as we direct in the recipes that follow. 
</P>
<P>
We think you'll agree that barbecue was never more delicious. Certainly it was 
never quicker or easier. 
</P>
<P>
BARBECUED SPARERIBS 
</P>
<P>
3 to 3 1/2 pounds lean spareribs, cut in 1- or 2-rib widths 
</P>
<P>
1 cup barbecue sauce 
</P>
<P>
Place ribs, meatiest side down and overlapping as needed, in microwave-safe 
12x8-inch casserole. Cover with vented plastic wrap and microwave on high (100% 
power) 5 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
Reduce power to medium (50% power) and microwave 15 minutes per pound, turning 
ribs over at half time and rearranging by moving undercooked ones to edge of 
casserole and re-covering with wax paper. 
</P>
<P>
Drain off all drippings. Pour sauce evenly over ribs. Cover with wax paper and 
microwave on medium 10 minutes. Makes 4 servings. 
</P>
<P>
Variations 
</P>
<P>
Crusty-Brown Barbecued Spareribs: 
</P>
<P>
Prepare ribs as directed. Remove from sauce and arrange in single layer in 
large roasting pan. Brush with additional barbecue sauce. Broil in preheated 
broiler 4 to 5 inches from heat 4 to 6 minutes until nicely browned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
