<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: CAMARILLO; 
</P>
<P>
PLANNERS SUGGEST ALLOWING RV SALES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RUSS CHARVONIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Camarillo Planning Commission on Tuesday recommended that the City Council 
amend the municipal code to allow the sales of recreational vehicles, equipment 
and services in areas zoned for limited manufacturing. 
</P>
<P>
Planning Director Matthew A. Boden said the change was proposed to satisfy a 
party interested in establishing an RV sales facility in the city. 
</P>
<P>
The amendment would require a minimum parcel of 15 acres for such uses. 
</P>
<P>
In another change to city ordinances, the commission recommended that the 
council allow certified farmers markets within the city limits. If the council 
approves the amendment, farmers markets, which are banned in the city, would be 
established. 
</P>
<P>
The Planning Commission also recommended changes to the city's General Plan 
relating to the use, disposal and transportation of hazardous materials. If the 
council approves the changes, the Planning Department would have greater 
control over the location, storage and use of chemicals that are deemed by the 
state to be hazardous. 
</P>
<P>
The council is expected to address these issues at its Aug. 8 meeting. 
</P>
<P>
A previously scheduled public hearing relating to a proposed ordinance 
regulating amateur radio antennas was postponed by the commission until Sept. 
4. RUSS CHARVONIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
