<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP BEAT: O.C. BLUES DUO FINDS SUCCESS AFTER FINDING ITS OWN STYLE; 
</P>
<P>
WILL BRADY AND JODI SIEGEL GAIN ACCLAIM AFTER GIVING UP AN UNCOMFORTABLE, 
HYBRID MUSICAL PERSONA AND DOING WHAT COMES NATURALLY? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE BOEHM 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For a while during their 10-year musical partnership, Will Brady and Jodi 
Siegel tried to be songsmiths, crafting would-be hits that they imagined being 
recorded by big-name pop stars. 
</P>
<P>
There also was a time when they would play Beatles songs, figuring that was 
what the people in the Orange County pubs and restaurants they played wanted to 
hear. 
</P>
<P>
Eventually, though, Brady and Siegel decided that they had to please themselves 
before they could be a hit with anybody else. The way to do that was by playing 
the blues. 
</P>
<P>
"We were trying so many styles. We were doing whatever it took to keep the 
gig," Siegel said as she and Brady sat in a Laguna Beach restaurant Tuesday 
night, recounting how Brady &amp; Siegel turned from an uncomfortable hybrid 
into an assured electric-blues duo. "People could see it wasn't true to who we 
were. They know when it's not authentic, or when you're not liking it." 
</P>
<P>
"You become non-recognizable, lose your identity," Brady chimed in without 
missing a conversational beat. Brady and Siegel have been working together long 
enough for their speech patterns to become as well-synchronized as their 
interwoven guitar lines. 
</P>
<P>
Brady, now 45, and Siegel, 34, found the answer to their musical identity 
crisis while noodling around between sets during those unsatisfying pop-hybrid 
days. Every time they had a few minutes to kill, they would unthinkingly start 
playing the blues. 
</P>
<P>
If that's what came naturally, the two guitarists decided, that's what they 
would be best off doing all the time. It was a smart decision: In the six or 
seven years since it was defined by the blues, Brady &amp; Siegel has evolved 
into an uncommonly fiery act that can reach back to the country blues tradition 
of Robert Johnson or leap forward into modern modes that echo such blues-based 
rockers as Little Feat, Bob Seger and Chuck Berry. 
</P>
<P>
Playing the blues didn't turn out to be a bad career move either. Instead of 
having to worry about keeping steady gigs, Brady and Siegel have settled into a 
regular routine on the local bar scene. Every Thursday night, they play at the 
Old Dana Point Cafe -- a gig they've held for 2 1/2 years -- and every Tuesday 
night for the past three months, they've been appearing at the Marine Room 
Tavern in Laguna Beach. In 1989, Brady and Siegel jumped into a Hyundai and 
took their blues around the country on a five-week tour, an experience that 
Brady said "gave us a feeling that it is possible to make all this happen" -- 
namely, stepping out of the small rooms of Orange County and onto a national 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
Opening for Albert King recently at the Coach House in San Juan Capistrano, 
Brady, a tall, affable man with a furrowed, balding pate, and Siegel, with a 
tight tangle of flaming-red hair framing sharp facial features, proved that 
they can win a crowd of deep-blues aficionados. When they were introduced, 
silence greeted the two guitarists' names. It was Freebo, their sideman for the 
night, who drew a ripple of applause in recognition of his past tenure as 
Bonnie Raitt's bass player. 
</P>
<P>
Before long, though, the audience was hollering approval for Brady's clean, 
stinging Telecaster solos, delivered with back-arching body English, and for 
Siegel's unfettered raucousness on slide guitar. Between liberal solo 
trade-offs, both members showed a convincing, intense way with a blues vocal. 
</P>
<P>
"You can't play little, polite blues," Brady said of the duo's aggressive 
method. "You have to go in there slugging. It keeps you honest." 
</P>
<P>
"You can't fake the blues," Siegel echoed. "Either you can play it or you 
can't. It has to be part of your makeup. I get up on that bandstand, it's my 
fun zone. I'm on vacation." 
</P>
<P>
Siegel grew up in Chicago, the world's blues capital, where Duane Allman's 
signature solos for the Allman Brothers Band inspired her to take up slide 
guitar. But most of her public performances as a teen-ager centered on folk and 
pop. 
</P>
<P>
She moved to Orange County at 19 to attend Orange Coast College. Gravitating to 
the local club scene, she ran into Brady. The guitarist had been in on the 
ground floor of the Orange County music scene, running the lights at the Golden 
Bear in Huntington Beach during the folk boom days of 1964-65, when Roger 
McGuinn and David Crosby would drop in to play. In the mid-1970s, Brady played 
bass for three years with Honk, the only Orange County rock band of that era to 
make a national name for itself. (He still takes part in Honk's periodic 
reunion shows.) 
</P>
<P>
The two played together occasionally, then struck up a close musical 
partnership when Siegel and her blues-aficionado husband, Sid Shultz, took a 
top-floor apartment in a Laguna Canyon house where Brady was the downstairs 
neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
After years of performing together, the duo's first bid for wider recognition 
was its 1989 debut album, "Beer &amp; Donuts," which was produced by Freebo and 
financed largely by Patrick Farrah, a wealthy benefactor who would show up at 
Brady &amp; Siegel gigs offering $100 for every Jimmy Reed song they would 
play. 
</P>
<P>
The album, available at Brady &amp; Siegel shows, includes only one original 
song. Entitled "She Takes What She Wants," it's a saucy number that allows 
Siegel, a temperate, low-keyed woman offstage, to step into the hot and rowdy 
onstage mode she often favors. 
</P>
<P>
"The next (album) will have a lot more original songs," Siegel said. "If you 
want to make it in the blues world, you've got to have some originality, your 
own sound that distinguishes you from everyone else." 
</P>
<P>
As a redhead who plays a mean, traditional-sounding blues slide guitar, Siegel 
knows that it will take some effort for her to establish a distinct identity. 
</P>
<P>
"People come up to me and say, 'Bonnie Raitt, right?' " she said. "I say, 'No, 
I'm not Bonnie Raitt.' I guess it's inevitable. I'm honored to be compared to a 
four-time Grammy winner, but I don't want people to think I'm trying to be her, 
because I'm not. Any female blues player who grew up in the '70s (had to be) 
influenced by her. But I was just as much influenced by Freddie King and Duane 
Allman and Etta James." 
</P>
<P>
While waiting to take their next career step, Brady, who still lives in Laguna 
Beach, supports himself primarily as a guitar teacher; Siegel, now a Dana Point 
resident, works days in a record store. 
</P>
<P>
The point, Siegel said, is to play for the enjoyment of it and let any future 
career ascent flow from that. "We'd be doing this anyway," she said. "We'd be 
doing it for our own personal therapy." 
</P>
<P>
"Any musician has a dream about being recognized by your peers and making 
enough money so you can relax a bit and not worry about where your next dime is 
coming from -- which is the way it's been all my life," Brady said. "But I'd be 
doing it if I were on a desert island." 
</P>
<P>
Siegel's deadpan response: "That's our next gig. I got a call from Gilligan." 
</P>
<P>
Brady &amp; Siegel's next gig is tonight at 9 at the Old Dana Point Cafe, 24701 
Street of the Golden Lantern, Dana Point. Admission is free. Information: (714) 
661-6003. The duo, augmented by a three-man band, also plays every Tuesday 
night at 8 at the Marine Room Tavern, 214 Ocean Ave., Laguna Beach. Admission: 
$2. Information: (714) 494-3027. 
</P>
<P>
OFF-TANGENT: A show next Wednesday by Agent Orange, the Swamp Zombies and 
Medicine Rattle will be the finale for Club Tangent, the weekly 
alternative-rock showcase at the Marquee in Westminster. 
</P>
<P>
However, Kitty Bash and Octavious, the two young promoters who have been 
putting on Club Tangent shows since last summer, appear to have found a new 
outlet: Starting next month, pending final agreement on a deal they have 
negotiated with owner Ray Camacho, they will book Thursday and Friday night 
shows at the Pink Cadillac in Anaheim under the moniker Tangent Productions. 
</P>
<P>
Club Tangent's four-month run at the Marquee is ending because it wasn't 
generating enough money, according to L. Trojan Tabak III, co-owner of the 
452-person-capacity club. 
</P>
<P>
Bash said the Marquee's identity as a haven for hard rock and heavy metal made 
it difficult to draw fans from the alternative-rock scene. Lacking a budget for 
advertising, she said, Club Tangent was not able to reach a potential clientele 
that normally wouldn't think of going to a heavy-metal club. Tangent drew an 
average of 80 to 100 concert-goers at the Marquee, Bash said, although in 
recent weeks, shows by Tender Fury and Caterwaul had boosted attendance to 180 
or 200. 
</P>
<P>
"We usually broke even, with sometimes a little extra (profit)," Bash said. 
</P>
<P>
From a club-owner's perspective, Tabak said, the Tangent crowd had a serious 
drawback: an inadequate thirst for bar drinks. 
</P>
<P>
"We served more water than anything else," he said, noting that the 
alternative-rock fans spent an average of $4 each on drinks, only half of the 
per-customer bar revenue on other weeknights. Tabak said he is considering 
offers from other promoters who have proposed booking blues acts, hard-rock 
bands or deejay dance nights on Wednesdays. 
</P>
<P>
Bash said Camacho invited the Club Tangent team to help him promote shows at 
the Pink Cadillac even before they learned that they were losing their slot at 
the Marquee. The Pink Cadillac already has established an alternative-rock 
identity with shows by some of the same bands that Club Tangent featured. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm kind of sad, because I think the Marquee was a really neat venue, but 
we're going to be picking up where we left off," Bash said. She said that she 
and Octavious expect to sign a contract to book Thursday nights in August at 
the Pink Cadillac, then expand to Thursdays and Fridays at the end of the 
month, beginning with an Aug. 31 concert by Firehose. 
</P>
<P>
COLOR IT ORANGE: Club Tangent's last concert will mark a homecoming for Agent 
Orange, which hasn't played its native county since a 1987 show at Night Moves. 
Now based in Los Angeles, the band features a splendid new lineup, with 
founding singer Mike Palm backed by Brent Liles and Derek O'Brien, the 
bass-and-drums team from Social Distortion's early days. 
</P>
<P>
According to manager Moss Jacobs, Agent Orange has negotiated a long-sought 
release from its recording contract with Enigma Records. "We're going to 
examine a lot of possibilities and look at taking the band to the next step," 
said Jacobs, who is general manager of Avalon Attractions. As part of its 
severance agreement with Enigma, Agent Orange will record a live album of songs 
previously released on the band's studio albums and EPs. The recording takes 
place Saturday night at the Roxy in Hollywood, where Agent Orange will play two 
shows with the tape rolling. 
</P>
<P>
T.S.O.L. GETS L.O.S.T.: Also cut free from Enigma -- but not nearly so happy 
about it -- is T.S.O.L. The long-running local hard-rock band was among the 
acts whose contracts were dropped in a major shake-up last week at the Culver 
City label. 
</P>
<P>
"It was quite a shock to all of us," said T.S.O.L.'s manager, Mike Zoto. The 
band's current album, "Strange Love," was to have been the first in a 
multi-album deal reached last year. "After you let it sink in and release your 
emotions, it could be OK," Zoto said. "You can't sit and dwell on it. You've 
got to go out and make something happen. But it's something very new and has to 
be pondered for a while." Currently on a national tour, T.S.O.L. is scheduled 
to play Aug. 11 at Jezebel's in Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
The Enigma shake-up has producer Jon St. James feeling nervous about the 
possible impact on Bardeux, another Orange County act on the label's roster. 
"It doesn't affect our (recording) deal, but it affects everyone at Enigma" in 
terms of the label's ability to promote current releases, St. James said. "I 
understand (Enigma) cut the staff considerably," he said. With a new Bardeux 
single, "Shangri-La," surfacing with dance-club play, he said, "I hope the 
company is there to back it up." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The local blues duo of Will Brady, left, and Jodi Siegel opened recently 
-- and successfully -- for Albert King at the Coach House. JOHN FUNG / Los 
Angeles Times; Photo, Jodi Siegel represents half of the Orange County blues 
duo Brady &amp; Siegel, which is gaining acclaim after finally finding its own 
musical niche. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Profile 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BLUES (MUSIC); MUSICIANS; SPIEGEL, JODI; BRADY, WILL 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071990-0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 249631 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 19, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
San Gabriel Valley; Part J; Page 1; Column 2 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
900 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HISTORIAN GATHERS LEGEND AND LORE OF ANGELES FOREST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERKLEY HUDSON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Environmental historian Donn E. Headley, midway through a 15-month project to 
probe legend and lore of the Angeles National Forest, had a confession. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm terrible with dates," the U.S. Forest Service historian said, as he 
reached into a gray metal cabinet in his Arcadia office, fishing for tales of 
how natural and man-made disasters have shaped the history of the Angeles and, 
in turn, greater Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
Headley's occasional uncertainty is understandable. His task these days is as 
formidable as the San Gabriel Mountains themselves. 
</P>
<P>
He is compiling a historical portrait of the Angeles, whose 100th anniversary 
will be celebrated in 1992. And his deadline is December. 
</P>
<P>
Before it was called the Angeles, it was the San Gabriel Timberlands Reserve, 
the eighth such forest to be created, and the first one established in 
California. Today, overseen by the U.S. Forest Service, the 650,000-acre 
preserve is one of the most heavily visited national forests in the country. 
</P>
<P>
Headley's inquiry encompasses a wide range of politics, science, ecology, 
governmental affairs and geology. He is most fascinated with the interaction of 
human beings and the natural world. "The thing that interests me most is the 
relationship between the (Angeles) forest and the city." 
</P>
<P>
Indeed, much of the impetus to set aside the land came from Los Angeles 
officials who saw the mountains' value principally as a source of water rather 
than a playground, and therefore a key in the development and marketing of 
Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
Headley, a UC Riverside doctoral candidate in history, is researching old-time 
stories of gold rushes and bandits and modern-day tales of how urban life has 
affected the flora and fauna. He was hired last September to work in the 
forest's Arcadia headquarters and is one of several historians who work for the 
Forest Service. 
</P>
<P>
But he spends more of his time in front of a word processor and in reading 
rooms of the Huntington Library and Pasadena Public Library than he does in the 
forest, assessing how the Angeles affects millions of people, physically, 
psychically and emotionally. 
</P>
<P>
What impresses him, he said, is "that for all the urban growth, the little 
effect that humans have had on the San Gabriel Mountains. They tend to endure. 
</P>
<P>
"This idea of Los Angeles as the center of an island with mountains around it," 
he said, "has been a central point in Southern California history for 150 
years." 
</P>
<P>
Already, Headley, 36, has begun writing his historical narrative. It will 
appear in a short popular history for the public and in another, more lengthy, 
volume to be used within the Forest Service. 
</P>
<P>
Some of Headley's historical tidbits have also been appearing in the 
"Grapevine," an in-house newsletter for Angeles employees. 
</P>
<P>
In the newsletter, Headley, whose area of expertise is water's role in Southern 
California, has discussed the 19th-Century water wars among feuding and 
drought-stricken residents of Duarte, Azusa and Covina. Gunfire and scuffles 
were often used to settle disagreements. 
</P>
<P>
Water shortages also affected those who lived in two turn-of-the-century 
utopian societies along the forest's borders: Los Terrenitos, which predated 
Tujunga, and Llano del Rio, a socialist community in the Antelope Valley. 
</P>
<P>
"Set at the edge of a vast continent, California has given rise to a restless 
search for new beginnings and perfection amid the region's unique environment," 
Headley wrote in a discussion of these communities, which by World War I had 
lost their utopian identities. 
</P>
<P>
He is also exploring the stories of people who shaped Los Angeles and the 
development of the Angeles. Prominent among these is Benjamin D. Wilson -- Mt. 
Wilson is named for him. He was an early Los Angeles mayor and the maternal 
grandfather of World War II hero Gen. George S. Patton Jr. 
</P>
<P>
And he is probing the scientific role of Mt. Wilson as a leading astronomical 
observatory site and how the San Dimas Experimental Forest in the Angeles has 
led the way in research on such topics as the effects of forest fires. 
</P>
<P>
The forest's past has provided a rich lode of disastrous happenings, including 
a 1900 fire known as the Big Fire, which burned for three months and destroyed 
22,000 acres. 
</P>
<P>
And the Great Flood of 1938, he said, killed 88 people. One hundred and 
twenty-seven more were never found. 
</P>
<P>
In his research, Headley has come across some poignant passages. One, recorded 
in a guest book from the San Gabriel River fishing camp of prominent Los 
Angeles attorney H. W. O'Melveny, was written in 1923 by George S. Patton, 
father of the general. 
</P>
<P>
"I saw this canyon first in 1868, when, as a boy of 12, I . . . caught my fill 
of big fish along the lonely stretches of virgin solitude," Patton wrote. "That 
was 55 years ago, and today as I walked alone in the same joyous silence, I 
experienced a deep sense of gratitude. . . ." 
</P>
<P>
Musing about this exceptional sylvan retreat and the woods around it, Patton 
urged, "May God guide our footsteps aright." And he wondered: "What of the 
future? The world is in dire distress. . . . " 
</P>
<P>
Ten years later, with the advent of flood control and hydroelectric power on 
the San Gabriel River, the Morris Dam flooded the land where the O'Melveny 
cabin stood. 
</P>
<P>
"These men hoped to have a balance between urban life and nature," Headley 
said. "But as time has gone on, the urban has taken over. Today we're possibly 
at a point of no return." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
