<HEADLINE>
<P>
6.4% EARNINGS DROP IN SECOND QUARTER REPORTED BY AT&amp;T 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. today reported its second-quarter 
earnings fell 6.4% due to lower equipment sales and unexpectedly high start-up 
costs for the company's new credit card. 
</P>
<P>
AT&amp;T said it earned $657 million, or 60 cents a share, in the quarter ended 
June 30, down from $699 million, or 65 cents a share, in the same quarter of 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
Revenue also fell, to $9.03 billion from $9.26 billion in the same quarter of 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
The company said the disappointing results were due mostly to slower sales of 
corporate telephone systems, data communications gear and equipment sold to the 
federal government, as well as unexpectedly high costs for processing 
applications for its Universal card, which combines a MasterCard or Visa with 
telephone charging privileges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
