<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOLLYWOOD PARK; 
</P>
<P>
SOLIS GAINS GROUND IN RIDING TITLE RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sports View came from off the pace to edge Golden Voyager by three-quarters of 
a length in the $37,000 allowance feature Wednesday at Hollywood Park as jockey 
Alex Solis and trainer D. Wayne Lukas scored key victories. 
</P>
<P>
For Solis, who also won the seventh race aboard favored Horsche, it was his 
51st winner of the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
That put him in a tie with Laffit Pincay Jr. for third place in the rider 
standings behind leader Pat Valenzuela (55 winners) and runner-up Gary Stevens 
(52). 
</P>
<P>
For Lukas, the nation's leading money-winning trainer, it was his 21st victory 
this meeting. That places Lukas one ahead of Ron McAnally for leading trainer 
of the spring/summer meet, which has five more days. 
</P>
<P>
Sports View, owned by Beal, Cox Jr. and Lukas, battled with Golden Voyager 
through most of the long stretch before prevailing in 1:35 2/5. Stevens was the 
rider on Golden Voyager, a 6/5 favorite in the field of six. 
</P>
<P>
Oh Wow came on late to take third, a nose behind Golden Voyager. 
</P>
<P>
The victory was worth $20,350 to the winner. 
</P>
<P>
It was Sports View's second win in eight races, with three seconds. Sports View 
has now earned $59,400. 
</P>
<P>
The winner paid $6.40, 3.20 and 2.40. Golden Voyager paid $2.60 and 2.10 and Oh 
Wow was $2.80 to show. (Charts, Section C) 
</P>
<P>
Trainer Ron McAnally put the final touches on Arkansas Derby winner Silver 
Ending over the weekend, as plans were completed for Sunday's $200,000 Swaps 
Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
"We worked the horse a mile Sunday," said McAnally. "He went in 1:39.1, and I 
was happy with the move." 
</P>
<P>
The 3-year-old Silver Hawk offspring has four wins in 10 starts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
