<HEADLINE>
<P>
CAUTHEN DRAWS BRITISH FINE FOR LATE PULLOUT FROM RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
American jockey Steve Cauthen was fined $1,800 today by the Jockey Club, the 
governing body of British horse racing, for pulling out of a race at the last 
minute in May. 
</P>
<P>
Cauthen refused to ride Pip Payne-trained colt Nicholas Payne at Leicester 
after he had weighed out. 
</P>
<P>
He was substituted by Richard Fox, who placed eighth in the race. 
</P>
<P>
Cauthen said after the hearing that he disagreed with the Jockey Club's 
decision and would do the same again. 
</P>
<P>
"I didn't think it was fair of the trainer to book me for that particular 
horse. There is no doubt he was a difficult ride -- everybody backed me," the 
former champion said. 
</P>
<P>
Cauthen can appeal the decision. The last time he appeared before the Jockey 
Club was in 1983, when he appealed unsuccessfully against an eight-day 
suspension for careless riding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
